    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1938-08-29T02:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1938-08-29T02:00:00-05:00" n="616"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d616">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">393.1115/3558: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul at Tsingtao</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Sokobin</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tsingtao</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-08-29T15:00:00+08:00"
                            >August 29, 1938—3 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received August 29—7 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>With reference to Peiping’s 503 of August 18, 3 p.m., regarding return of
                    missionaries to interior, the Japanese Consulate General has now given
                    permission to Americans to travel on Tsingtao-Tsinanfu Railway. Through
                    cooperation of Japanese Consul General the railway will give special facilities
                    for transportation. About 30 Americans will travel to Tsinanfu and to points
                    south on the Tientsin–Pukow Railway. They propose to leave Thursday or Friday of
                    this week.</p>
                <p>Sent to Peiping, Chungking, Tientsin. By mail to Tokyo.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Sokobin</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
